      <div xml:id="NA238-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaimakaḷ paruvaṅkaṇ ṭaḻintatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how SHE is desolate when seeing the season.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA238">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vaṟaṅkola vīnta kāṉattuk kuṟumpūṅ</l>
<l>            kōtai makaḷir kuḻūunirai kaṭuppa</l>
<l>            vaṇṭuvāy tiṟappa viṇṭa piṭava</l>
<l>            mālai yanti mālatar naṇṇiya</l>
<l>            paruvañ ceyta karuvi māmaḻai </l>
<l>            yavarnilai yaṟimō vīṅkeṉa varutal</l>
<l>            cāṉṟōrp puraivatō vaṉṟē māṉṟuṭa</l>
<l>            ṉuravuru muraṟu nīriṟ paranta</l>
<l>            pāmpupai maḻuṅka laṉṟiyu māṇṭa</l>
<l>            kaṉiyā neñcat tāṉu </l>
<l>            miṉiya vallaniṉ ṉiṭinavil kuralē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O great big rain made in season,</l>
<l rend="indent">situated<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">naṇṇiya</term> is slightly uncomfortable here, and T.V.G. wants to connect it with the <term xml:lang="ta">avar</term> of line 6 (which is very much in the tradition of <term xml:lang="ta">Nacciṉārkkiṉiyar</term>), but the point might be that the season probably has also reached the road, not only HER village.</note> on the big road in evening twilight,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with Piṭavus that have unfolded when the bees opened</l>
<l rend="indent2">[their bud-]mouths</l>
<l rend="indent3">as a gathering row of women [wearing] garland swith all short</l>
<l rend="indent3">flowers in the forest that was perished, afflicted by drought,</l>
<l>please find out(?) about his state.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Is it great for someone noble</l>
<l>to come just here<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">īṅku eṉa</term>: again this strange exclusive use of <term xml:lang="ta">eṉa</term> (cf. <term xml:lang="ta">iṉi eṉa</term> in NA 233.5).</note>? It is not,</l>
<l rend="indent">– with a voice that utters your thunder, sweet [and] strong,</l>
<l rend="indent">into [his] glorious [but] unmelting heart<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">neñcattāṉ</term> can be taken as a locative, but what of the -<term xml:lang="ta">um</term>?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">besides the snake’s hood becoming dull(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pāmpu pai maḻuṅkal</term>: this does not really make sense, and with a look at a close parallel in the KT, one feels tempted to emend into <term xml:lang="ta">pāmpu pai v-aḻuṅkal</term>, the snake’s hood being spoiled (cf. KT 185.5+391.3 <term xml:lang="ta">pāmpu pai avi-tal</term>).</note>, sprawled<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">paranta</term>: the <term xml:lang="ta">pey</term>. demands a construction with <term xml:lang="ta">pāmpu</term>, and if it is the snake (or several of them) that have been dislocated by the rush of water, we could also understand the oblique mark <term xml:lang="ta">nīriṉ</term>, which would be strange if it were the direct object of <term xml:lang="ta">paranta</term>.  Actually one would want an absolutive in order to take <term xml:lang="ta">kural</term> (or you) as the subject, and not <term xml:lang="ta">pāmpu</term>.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">in the water when the strong thunder roars,</l>
<l rend="indent3">all mixed up together(?).</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
